WEBVTT

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:07.640
Let's begin with talquitamib as bridging therapy before CAR-T. Many of you are familiar with

00:00:07.640 --> 00:00:16.440
the data that's been published, mostly retrospective work, where talquitamib has shown its efficacy.

00:00:16.440 --> 00:00:20.680
The question is, should it become a standard of care?

00:00:20.680 --> 00:00:26.580
And if it does, then how do we go about post-CAR-T relapses and where does talquitamib fit

00:00:26.580 --> 00:00:29.620
in there and resistant mechanisms?

00:00:29.620 --> 00:00:32.560
Okay, so these are my disclosures.

00:00:32.560 --> 00:00:37.140
So talquitamib you can see here is part of the NCCN recommendations.

00:00:37.140 --> 00:00:42.400
I think it got cut off, but there is at the bottom star an indication saying that talquitamib

00:00:42.400 --> 00:00:46.920
can be used as a bridging therapy.

00:00:46.920 --> 00:00:49.180
So but why GPRC 5D bridging?

00:00:49.180 --> 00:00:53.520
We have a gap of almost six to eight weeks where the CAR-T cells get manufactured from

00:00:53.520 --> 00:00:56.560
the time of apheresis to the actual patient getting infected.

00:00:56.560 --> 00:01:09.800
And by this time, patients may have already been exposed to your conventional, you know, your POMs and your IMIDs and your carfilzomibs, unless it's really second-line myeloma.

00:01:10.500 --> 00:01:18.720
And so, it offers, it's a new target because it preserves your BCMA as that's going to be your CAR-T-cell target.

00:01:19.500 --> 00:01:22.760
You don't want to use the BCMA by specifics.

00:01:23.260 --> 00:01:34.520
And I know Dr. Garfall made a comment about the cohort C in CAR-T, but there is some reduced efficacy when we follow one BCMA by another BCMA.

00:01:34.820 --> 00:01:41.860
And we try not to use conventional chemotherapy because that might compromise T-cell, have an impact on T-cell biology.

00:01:42.200 --> 00:01:52.860
So, I think with GPRC5D, especially if it's done post-apheresis, you preserve BCMA, your T-cell fitness is protected.

00:01:53.260 --> 00:01:55.820
And then you have rapid-onset disease control.

00:01:55.820 --> 00:02:01.300
In my practice, I sometimes just do the ramp-up and not even a full cycle.

00:02:01.300 --> 00:02:08.520
That allows for enough disease control where I don't have to expose them to longer durations of the telcoidamab and bring on toxicity.

00:02:09.460 --> 00:02:11.840
And so, that makes itself be sufficient.

00:02:12.900 --> 00:02:16.680
So, we have two single institution experiences that I present here.

00:02:16.680 --> 00:02:22.900
One is the UAB and the other one is the Emory with, you know, patient, about eight patients to 25 patients.

00:02:23.020 --> 00:02:28.400
And over here, many of them were, you know, median line, prior lines of therapy were four.

00:02:28.480 --> 00:02:30.180
So, these were heavily pre-treated patients.

00:02:30.800 --> 00:02:37.860
And then they go on to have high numbers of efficacy.

00:02:37.860 --> 00:02:48.000
So, five out of six patients where patients received telcoidamab in the God-B abstract and 22 out of the 25 patients who received telcoidamab.

00:02:48.940 --> 00:02:52.980
And then I think there is a work done by Dr. Fundrea.

00:02:53.020 --> 00:03:01.740
And where they show that, look at 52 patients who've got in-tech telcoidamab, conventional chemotherapy, and anti-CD38.

00:03:02.080 --> 00:03:10.300
And I think that patients who had bispecific bridging therapy had 100% overall response rate versus 46% with other bridges.

00:03:11.200 --> 00:03:21.600
And then in terms of CAR-T kinetics, you saw early CD4 and delayed CD8 expansion, which may be independently associated with deep responses.

00:03:21.740 --> 00:03:22.780
And then in terms of...

00:03:22.780 --> 00:03:28.120
And then in terms of clonal dynamics, higher T-cell colonality at apheresis, which may prime for CAR-T cell synergy.

00:03:29.620 --> 00:03:43.160
This is the U.S. Myeloma Immunotherapy Consortium had a study led by Dr. Tuckall, where they looked at 134 patients, both who received Cilta-Cell and Ida-Cell as standard of care.

00:03:43.780 --> 00:03:52.120
19 patients did have telcoidamab prior to apheresis, and 115 patients had it after apheresis.

00:03:52.540 --> 00:03:56.840
Ultimately, out of the 100, so 89% received it.

00:03:57.420 --> 00:04:01.780
And then of these, 15 patients did not get infused.

00:04:02.460 --> 00:04:08.220
There were seven progressions, and there was manufacturing failure and patient decision.

00:04:08.500 --> 00:04:13.600
So ultimately, out of the 100, 1998 were Cilta-Cell and 21 were Ida-Cell.

00:04:14.060 --> 00:04:21.780
And you can see over here with the median follow-up 6.9 months in this 134 patients, the median PFS and overall survival was not reached.

00:04:22.300 --> 00:04:26.040
EMD was the only independent predictor of inferior PFS and OS.

00:04:26.600 --> 00:04:33.820
And then you can see that 42% of the patients deepened their response after CAR-T versus their telcoidamab response.

00:04:34.700 --> 00:04:43.820
The Sankey diagram even illustrates that, you know, 19% of patients achieved CR before CAR-T with just telcoidamab alone.

00:04:44.260 --> 00:04:47.680
And then even post-CAR-T responses deepened.

00:04:48.420 --> 00:04:51.540
15 patients, as I mentioned before, never reached infusion.

00:04:52.060 --> 00:04:57.220
So if the patients who responded to telcoidamab had deeper responses post-CAR-T.

00:04:57.800 --> 00:04:59.820
Now let's talk about toxicity.

00:05:00.200 --> 00:05:03.660
Dr. Krishnan did mention that in her presentation.

00:05:04.260 --> 00:05:13.040
So 60% of GPRC5D specific toxicities were seen, but they were mostly grade 1 and 2, and they did end up resolving.

00:05:13.500 --> 00:05:20.960
70% of patients had oral changes, 38% of the patients had skin changes, and grade 3 and 4 was less than 1%.

00:05:21.820 --> 00:05:24.080
And the nail changes were only 17%.

00:05:24.080 --> 00:05:30.380
And these were probably low because the duration and exposure of the bispecific was not prolonged.

00:05:30.380 --> 00:05:45.900
I think the median on days were about 23% and also doing this as we go into CAR-T, GPRC, you know, with GPRC bispecifics, you tend to preserve your humoral response immunity and so you don't get hypogamma and increase your risk of infection.

00:05:46.400 --> 00:05:47.560
So that's that.

00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:51.580
But I think when we use this, I'm very pleased in seeing this response.

00:05:51.580 --> 00:05:54.700
And I use it, but I don't think I use it willy-nilly.

00:05:54.960 --> 00:06:07.700
If I can use, if someone doesn't have a high burden of disease and they are not heavily refractory, I tend to go with my carfilzavib, my IMIDS, in first and after first relapse or second relapse.

00:06:07.960 --> 00:06:20.680
Because we now have data in terms of a study that Dr. Krishnan highlighted by Holly Lee from Dr. Nizar's lab showing that, you know, patients who had gotten prior GPRCs,

00:06:21.340 --> 00:06:21.840
they didn't have a high burden of disease and they had a high risk of getting GPRC bispecifics, they didn't have a high risk of getting GPRC bispecifics.

00:06:21.840 --> 00:06:40.960
So one of the main mechanisms in which they relapsed was that there was a large release in their GPRC, GPRC 5D locus, there were monolithic losses, which can lead to reduced GPRC expression on the surface and, and so, you know, we don't, we don't want to lose this as a treatment option, I think even post-CAR-T-T.

00:06:42.360 --> 00:06:45.680
So that's why I don't tend to willy-nilly use it.

00:06:45.780 --> 00:06:50.800
I reserve it for patients where I don't, I don't want to do chemotherapy, but they have a decent burden of disease.

00:06:51.100 --> 00:07:05.280
And my other viable, effective treatment options just don't, are not, are not available to me because we do now have some even evidence of these patients who are GPRC and BCMA refractory.

00:07:05.280 --> 00:07:10.980
So your haptic refractory patients and their outcomes and their median overall survival is 12.8 months.

00:07:11.040 --> 00:07:20.240
And at the bottom, you can see one of the mechanisms of where we see the mutation.

00:07:20.860 --> 00:07:21.600
Sorry.

00:07:21.600 --> 00:07:26.760
So I think for questions for debate, should talc bridge before BCMA-CAR-T-T become the standard of care?

00:07:27.100 --> 00:07:28.460
What is the optimal washout?

00:07:28.520 --> 00:07:30.700
This is something I, we debate all the time.

00:07:30.780 --> 00:07:39.180
If I can extend the time between my last talc dose to my CAR-T, I do, keeping in mind the patient's tempo and disease in mind.

00:07:39.540 --> 00:07:41.580
And what should actually be your response measure?

00:07:41.760 --> 00:07:44.020
What should it be your soluble BCMA decline?

00:07:44.160 --> 00:07:48.700
I have that test available at my institution, many, many other places that don't.

00:07:48.700 --> 00:07:50.620
And I think does the short course.

